00:46:09,607 --> 00:46:12,201
Only New York?

478
00:46:13,967 --> 00:46:15,161
This is my stop.

479
00:46:17,207 --> 00:46:20,085
May I walk with you a little then?

480
00:46:20,247 --> 00:46:22,886
That, sir, would be too bold.

481
00:46:39,847 --> 00:46:40,882
Good morning.

482
00:46:48,967 --> 00:46:52,323
For every lay we had a different name.

483
00:46:52,487 --> 00:46:54,682
An "angler" put a hook
on the end of a stick...

484
00:46:54,847 --> 00:46:57,839
...to drop behind
store windows and doors.

485
00:46:58,007 --> 00:47:01,443
An "autumn diver"
picked your pocket in church.

486
00:47:01,607 --> 00:47:04,041
A "badger" gets a fellow
into bed with a girl...

487
00:47:04,207 --> 00:47:07,040
...then robs his pockets
while they're on the go.

488
00:47:07,527 --> 00:47:11,122
Jenny was a "bludget,"
a girl pickpocket...

489
00:47:11,287 --> 00:47:15,041
...and a "turtledove."

490
00:47:16,647 --> 00:47:19,719
A turtledove goes uptown
dressed like a housemaid...

491
00:47:19,887 --> 00:47:23,482
...picks out a fine house
and goes right through the back door.

492
00:47:23,887 --> 00:47:25,115
Robs you blind.

493
00:47:27,007 --> 00:47:30,158
It takes a lot of sand
to be a turtledove.

494
00:47:51,367 --> 00:47:55,155
I'll have my medal back. Oh, Jesus!

495
00:48:01,487 --> 00:48:03,398
Don't do that again.

496
00:48:03,567 --> 00:48:06,286
Listen! I said, don't do that...

497
00:48:06,927 --> 00:48:08,963
Go back to the Points
and leave me to my business...

498
00:48:09,127 --> 00:48:11,960
...or I will open your throat,
so help me God.

499
00:48:15,167 --> 00:48:17,044
All right.

500
00:48:18,567 --> 00:48:20,444
Go on then.

501
00:48:22,567 --> 00:48:24,398
I would.

502
00:48:25,887 --> 00:48:27,206
Go on then.

503
00:48:48,607 --> 00:48:51,167
Now give me back my medal.

504
00:48:51,527 --> 00:48:53,677
Make it quick!

505
00:49:00,527 --> 00:49:03,360
I don't know which one's yours.

506
00:49:09,687 --> 00:49:11,962
Suppose I help myself to everything?

507
00:49:14,647 --> 00:49:16,319
Suppose you do.

508
00:49:53,887 --> 00:49:56,560
May I walk with you a little then?

509
00:50:04,767 --> 00:50:07,361
What do you suppose a fellow
could earn here in a day?

510
00:50:07,687 --> 00:50:10,724
- Maybe we could pal in together.
- Oh, I think you're a bit...

511
00:50:10,887 --> 00:50:15,324
...rough for this sort of game.
Besides, I work alone.

512
00:50:15,487 --> 00:50:18,285
Alone? Well, what do you quarter
to the Butcher?

513
00:50:18,447 --> 00:50:20,642
- Me? Nothing.
- Nothing?

514
00:50:20,807 --> 00:50:23,196
The Butcher and me
have a special arrangement.

515
00:50:30,367 --> 00:50:34,042
- I don't want to see you again.
- Well, I don't blame you.

516
00:50:34,847 --> 00:50:37,441
Pennies in their pockets
and hope in their eyes...

517
00:50:37,607 --> 00:50:39,598
...they peer to the west...

518
00:50:39,767 --> 00:50:44,158
...searching the horizon
for a glimpse of land and salvation.

519
00:50:45,887 --> 00:50:47,400
A glimpse of America.

520
00:50:47,567 --> 00:50:50,764
Seeing all this poverty must be
most unsettling, Miss Schermerhorn.

521
00:50:50,927 --> 00:50:54,397
Some days, of course,
the uptown gangs come down to us.

522
00:50:54,967 --> 00:50:58,482
The Schermerhorns was one
of the oldest families in New York.

523
00:50:58,647 --> 00:51:00,160
They didn 't run the city...

524
00:51:00,327 --> 00:51:02,636
...but they was listened
to carefully by them that did.

525
00:51:02,807 --> 00:51:04,525
Commissioner Brunt
said you wished to view...

526
00:51:04,687 --> 00:51:06,962
...the Points in all
its splendor and squalor.

527
00:51:07,127 --> 00:51:09,277
"Spare nothing concerning
the conditions," said he.

528
00:51:09,447 --> 00:51:12,245
Yeah, nothing except
our safety, constable.

529
00:51:12,407 --> 00:51:15,843
I'm sure we can be in no danger
while we're in the constable's company.

530
00:51:16,007 --> 00:51:19,443
Quite so, madam. Witness.

531
00:51:26,287 --> 00:51:29,279
- Shall we continue on?
- What, you dare to leave it there?

532
00:51:29,447 --> 00:51:33,838
Safe as a bank, Mr. Greeley,
since all know i�s mine.

533
00:51:34,007 --> 00:51:39,035
- Is that man drunk?
- Dead as Good friday, miss.

534
00:51:43,127 --> 00:51:45,402
- Good day to you, Mulraney.
- Boys.

535
00:51:45,567 --> 00:51:47,205
- Jack.
- Slum sociable?

536
00:51:47,367 --> 00:51:49,756
Fact-finding. Reforms-studying.

537
00:51:49,927 --> 00:51:52,282
- May I present...?
- The Schermerhorns of fifth Avenue...

538
00:51:52,447 --> 00:51:54,563
...scarcely require
an introduction from you.

539
00:51:54,727 --> 00:51:57,924
Schermerhorn, indeed. Their daughter.
This gentleman, of course...

540
00:51:58,087 --> 00:52:01,204
Horace Greeley, the famous publisher.
A pleasure and an honor.

541
00:52:01,607 --> 00:52:04,280
- Of the Tribune.
- I'm William Cutting.

542
00:52:05,607 --> 00:52:07,837
How do you do, Mr. Cutting?

543
00:52:09,287 --> 00:52:13,280
As of this moment, extremely well,
thank you. How do you do?

544
00:52:13,767 --> 00:52:15,723
Orange blossom. Delicious.

545
00:52:15,887 --> 00:52:18,082
- Mr. Cutting is...
- What a peach.

546
00:52:18,247 --> 00:52:20,158
She could have a fine career
on the stage.

547
00:52:20,327 --> 00:52:22,795
...one of Five Points' local...
- A pleasure to meet you.

548
00:52:22,967 --> 00:52:24,446
...leaders.
- Mr. Greeley.

549
00:52:24,607 --> 00:52:26,563
- Pleased to meet you.
- The Points welcomes you.

550
00:52:26,727 --> 00:52:29,560
You are welcome to these streets
and will pass in safety.

551
00:52:30,647 --> 00:52:35,198
Oh, I'll see to their safety.
Thank you, Bill. There we are.

552
00:52:35,367 --> 00:52:38,643
Good day, lads.
Criminal's braggadocio, you see.

553
00:52:38,807 --> 00:52:42,880
- He knows who I am.
- You're well-known in these parts.

554
00:52:43,207 --> 00:52:46,324
I must say that I find
that strangely flattering.

555
00:52:46,487 --> 00:52:49,081
- I never did like crushers.
- Well, draw it mild, son.

556
00:52:49,247 --> 00:52:53,604
Happy Jack don't fill his lungs
without I tell him he may do so.

557
00:53:05,647 --> 00:53:09,435
Do you think my watch
would be safe up on that lamppost, Bill?

558
00:53:10,727 --> 00:53:13,036
Why don't you hang it up there and see?

559
00:53:15,767 --> 00:53:16,882
Someday.

560
00:53:18,647 --> 00:53:20,080
Someday is right.

561
00:53:21,767 --> 00:53:23,758
This a new lad?

562
00:53:24,207 --> 00:53:29,486
Just another bastard son of Erin
I folded in the warmth of my embrace.

563
00:53:32,247 --> 00:53:34,761
- Hey!
- I just want to see your face, son.

564
00:53:34,927 --> 00:53:36,997
No harm intended.

565
00:53:59,167 --> 00:54:02,159
You get to know a lot butchering meat.

566
00:54:03,407 --> 00:54:05,841
We're made up of the same things:
Flesh and blood...

567
00:54:06,007 --> 00:54:09,158
...tissue, organs.

568
00:54:09,327 --> 00:54:11,921
I love to work with pigs.

569
00:54:12,087 --> 00:54:17,161
The nearest thing in nature to the flesh
of a man is the flesh of a pig.

570
00:54:17,327 --> 00:54:19,397
- Pig, huh?
- Tha�s right.

571
00:54:19,567 --> 00:54:22,001
This is for you, mother.

572
00:54:24,407 --> 00:54:25,681
There you go.

573
00:54:25,847 --> 00:54:28,759
- God bless you, Mr. Cutting.
- God bless you.

574
00:54:28,927 --> 00:54:33,205
- She ain't really my mother.
- I knew that, Bill.

575
00:54:37,127 --> 00:54:39,357
This is the liver.

576
00:54:39,847 --> 00:54:41,565
The kidneys.

577
00:54:41,727 --> 00:54:43,479
The heart.

578
00:54:43,647 --> 00:54:46,878
This is a wound.
The stomach will bleed and bleed.

579
00:54:47,047 --> 00:54:50,244
This is a kill. This is a kill.

580
00:54:51,047 --> 00:54:54,323
The main artery. This is a kill.

581
00:54:55,647 --> 00:54:57,524
You try.

582
00:55:00,447 --> 00:55:01,846
Go ahead.

583
00:55:26,607 --> 00:55:28,996
The lung. Good.
Don't foul the blade on the rib.

584
00:55:29,167 --> 00:55:31,237
Very good. Main artery.

585
00:55:31,407 --> 00:55:34,080
Bleed him slow.
Let him think about it for a while.

586
00:55:34,247 --> 00:55:36,966
Slow death. Good.

587
00:55:38,327 --> 00:55:41,524
You'll each bill the city $5000
a month for supplies and services...

588
00:55:41,687 --> 00:55:43,405
...of which you'll receive 10%.

589
00:55:43,567 --> 00:55:47,242
Bill! Mr. Killoran will work out
the details. Thank you, gentlemen.

590
00:55:47,407 --> 00:55:50,319
Tha�s how we do things
around Tammany, gentlemen.

591
00:55:50,487 --> 00:55:52,318
Who's this then?

592
00:55:53,287 --> 00:55:55,118
Thank you, boys.

593
00:55:55,287 --> 00:55:57,278
Good day, sir.

594
00:56:08,407 --> 00:56:10,841
You got something on your mind?

595
00:56:13,487 --> 00:56:15,478
Bill's taken quite a liking to you.

596
00:56:18,087 --> 00:56:21,716
Now, if you're up to something, bene.

597
00:56:21,887 --> 00:56:24,003
Only I don't want no part in it.

598
00:56:28,487 --> 00:56:31,843
I was in Hellgate for 16 years.

599
00:56:32,207 --> 00:56:34,482
I'm just trying to make my way is all.

600
00:56:34,647 --> 00:56:36,763
Just like you.

601
00:56:37,767 --> 00:56:39,837
Unless, of course,
you got a better notion?

602
00:56:41,287 --> 00:56:42,356
No.

603
00:56:43,287 --> 00:56:47,200
Bill, I can't get a day's work done
for all the good citizens...

604
00:56:47,367 --> 00:56:50,723
...coming in here to harass me
about crime in the Points.

605
00:56:50,887 --> 00:56:53,242
Some even go so far
as to accuse Tammany...

606
00:56:53,407 --> 00:56:57,002
...of connivance in this so-called
rampant criminality.

607
00:56:57,167 --> 00:57:00,159
What am I to do? I can't have this.
Something has to be done.

608
00:57:00,327 --> 00:57:02,602
- What do you have in mind?
- I don't know.

609
00:57:02,767 --> 00:57:04,962
I think maybe we should
hang someone.

610
00:57:06,167 --> 00:57:08,203
- Who?
- No one important, necessarily.

611
00:57:08,367 --> 00:57:12,758
Average men will do.
Back-alley amusers with no affiliations.

612
00:57:12,927 --> 00:57:16,476
- How many?
- Three or four.

613
00:57:16,807 --> 00:57:20,197
- Which?
- Four.

614
00:57:20,767 --> 00:57:24,203
You stand here convicted varyingly...

615
00:57:24,367 --> 00:57:27,359
...of lewdness, jack-rolling...

616
00:57:27,527 --> 00:57:31,122
...sneak-thievery,
chloral-hydrating...

617
00:57:31,287 --> 00:57:33,881
...sodomy, strangulation...

618
00:57:34,047 --> 00:57:38,757
...and enthusiastic corruption
of the public good.

619
00:57:40,167 --> 00:57:41,998
- We all go someday, huh?
- Chin up.

620
00:57:42,167 --> 00:57:44,283
Handsome bunch of gallows fruit.
There's my old friend.

621
00:57:44,447 --> 00:57:47,280
- How are you feeling, Arthur?
- I'm okay. I'm okay.

622
00:57:47,447 --> 00:57:50,359
Say hello to Amsterdam. Nearly
fishhooked McGloin the other day.

623
00:57:50,527 --> 00:57:51,642
- How do you do?
- Nearly.

624
00:57:51,807 --> 00:57:53,445
See you dressed for the occasion.

625
00:57:53,607 --> 00:57:55,677
You know me,
always like to look me best.

626
00:57:55,847 --> 00:57:57,280
Tha�s the spirit.

627
00:57:58,727 --> 00:58:01,525
Nice locket.
I'll give you a dollar for it.

628
00:58:01,687 --> 00:58:03,279
L�s me mother's.

629
00:58:03,447 --> 00:58:04,800
Dollar and a half?

630
00:58:05,727 --> 00:58:07,001
Done.

631
00:58:10,407 --> 00:58:11,840
We'll miss you, Arthur.

632
00:58:12,007 --> 00:58:14,077
- See you in the hot country, Seamus.
- Hot corn!

633
00:58:14,247 --> 00:58:17,284
Ears of early white corn!
Hot corn!

634
00:58:21,287 --> 00:58:23,198
Is my son present here?

635
00:58:24,887 --> 00:58:26,400
Where's my little fella?

636
00:58:28,487 --> 00:58:30,205
Look at your dad.

637
00:58:30,407 --> 00:58:32,318
Farewell, dear boy.

638
00:58:33,687 --> 00:58:38,363
I never struck a foul blow,
nor turned a card.

639
00:58:39,847 --> 00:58:43,203
May God greet me as a friend.

640
00:59:06,247 --> 00:59:09,603
And grace my fears relieved

641
00:59:09,767 --> 00:59:13,601
How precious
Did that grace appear

642
00:59:13,767 --> 00:59:16,486
That night,
the reformers held a dance.

643
00:59:16,647 --> 00:59:19,036
That was the Five Points, all right.

644
00:59:19,207 --> 00:59:22,358
Hangings of a morning,
dancings of an evening.

645
00:59:22,527 --> 00:59:24,358
- Sure meself, but...

646
00:59:24,527 --> 00:59:27,246
...i�s not a matter of words.
I can tell by the way she smiles at me.

647
00:59:27,407 --> 00:59:29,284
- She smiles at a lot of people.
- Sir.

648
00:59:29,447 --> 00:59:30,675
You don't know her.

649
00:59:30,847 --> 00:59:34,237
A penny of gratitude
for a fighting Irishman, young sir.

650
00:59:37,327 --> 00:59:40,558
- You from Kerry?
- I am, sir. I am.

651
00:59:41,487 --> 00:59:44,001
- It ain't much.
- Thank you, sir. Thank you.

652
00:59:44,167 --> 00:59:46,635
Ladies and gentlemen,
we are delighted to see...

653
00:59:46,807 --> 00:59:50,117
...so many young faces
at our first annual Mission dance.

654
00:59:50,287 --> 00:59:52,084
This'll be a real ballum rancum, eh?

655
00:59:52,247 --> 00:59:55,159
The Mission welcomes Christians
of every stamp...

656
00:59:55,327 --> 00:59:58,763
...and we are particularly happy
to greet our Roman Catholic friends...

657
00:59:58,927 --> 01:00:00,804
...who join us here tonight.

658
01:00:01,047 --> 01:00:04,676
- Ladies! Come with me. Come with me.
- Shall we dance?

659
01:00:04,847 --> 01:00:07,566
We're going to start the dancing
in just a moment.

660
01:00:07,727 --> 01:00:08,716
No.

661
01:00:09,447 --> 01:00:13,122
- Good evening, Reverend.
- Good evening, Your Holiness.

662
01:00:15,127 --> 01:00:16,276
Good evening, Reverend.

663
01:00:16,607 --> 01:00:19,405
Looks as though
you should have shaved closer.

664
01:00:23,047 --> 01:00:26,244
Good evening, Reverend.
I do beg your pardon.

665
01:00:30,407 --> 01:00:32,159
Miss...?

666
01:00:35,847 --> 01:00:38,964
- Everdeane.
- Miss Everdeane.

667
01:00:50,607 --> 01:00:55,362
Now, gentlemen, over here,
if you don't mind. Thank you.

668
01:00:55,527 --> 01:00:58,246
Open it. Hold it up.

669
01:01:00,367 --> 01:01:02,244
Into the mirror.

670
01:01:52,807 --> 01:01:54,206
That one.

671
01:01:55,807 --> 01:01:59,004
Our queen has chosen.

672
01:02:16,807 --> 01:02:18,286
Sir...

673
01:02:18,447 --> 01:02:20,802
...your lady.
- Right.

674
01:02:20,967 --> 01:02:23,765
Regular services are held
at the church at 6 and 8.

675
01:02:23,927 --> 01:02:24,962
Go to hell.

676
01:02:34,007 --> 01:02:36,077
- What do you think you're doing?
- Dancing.

677
01:02:36,247 --> 01:02:39,364
- I said, why'd you pick me?
- Tha�s none of your business.

678
01:02:39,527 --> 01:02:41,324
Would you mind telling me?

679
01:02:41,927 --> 01:02:43,360
I'm sorry.

680
01:02:44,287 --> 01:02:46,278
Goddamn it!

681
01:02:46,847 --> 01:02:50,396
I'm sorry.
I'm not much of a dancer.

682
01:02:50,567 --> 01:02:52,319
Just try to keep calm.

683
01:02:52,487 --> 01:02:56,560
- I never been to a stepping-ken before.
- L�s best not to look down.

684
01:02:58,607 --> 01:03:01,167
